<DOC><DOCNO> AP890815-0083 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-89 1118EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-Robinette     08-15 0170</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Robinette,160</SECOND><HEAD>Iran-Contra Witness in Hospital With Heart Attack</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former CIA operative who was a key figure inthe Iran-Contra trial of Oliver L. North is hospitalized aftersuffering a heart attack.   Glenn Robinette, now a security consultant, said in a telephoneinterview today that suffered the attack last Friday and is expectedto remain hospitalized until the weekend.   Robinette testified at North's trial that he and the formerNational Security Council aide created phony documents to disguisethe fact that someone else had paid for a $16,000 security fence atNorth's home.   North was convicted on three counts in the Iran-Contra affair,including the acceptance of an illegal gratuity _ the fence.   Robinette, who testified under a grant of immunity, said hereceived money for the fence from arms dealer Richard V. Secord.Secord, who worked with North in the plan to divert money from thesale of weapons to Iran to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels, isscheduled to go on trial Nov. 13.</TEXT></DOC>